summary.seg: This Gospel book was probably copied in the 13th century, as indicated by the style of script. This remains quite restrained through most of the manuscript, but towards the end of the main text it becomes increasingly ornate and florid, as though in celebration of the imminent completion of the work. The manuscript's ornamentation is monochrome and relatively simple, but carries the distinctive feature of integrating the headpieces preceding three of the Gospels with the decorated initial letters of the text into a single piece of ornament (Part III, ff. 3r, 93r, 151r).

At the end of the manuscript, the Gospels are followed, as was common, by a summary lectionary giving references to identify the portions of the text to be read in the course of the liturgical cycle (Part II, ff. 1r-5v). However, at some later date, probably in the 14th or 15th century, another summary lectionary was added, on small paper leaves bound into the front of the manuscript, for reasons which are unclear. This presently contains only a portion of the synaxarion, the lection cycle of the movable calendar beginning from Easter, omitting the opening section of this sequence, the "weeks of John" between Easter and Pentecost. It is uncertain whether this section has been lost or if it was never included. The menologion, containing the lections of the fixed calendar, was evidently never included in this supplement. These additional folios also contain an introductory hypothesis to the Gospel of Matthew, the first to appear in the usual sequence (Part II, f. 6r).

In the early modern period the manuscript was owned by the Monastery of the Pantokrator on Mount Athos, and lent by the monastery to a priest named Silvestros, as recorded by a note which stipulated the monastery's right to reclaim it at any time. It was later acquired from the Pantokrator, along with many other manuscripts, by the classicist Richard Bentley (1662-1742), Master of Trinity, and bequeathed to the college with the rest of his collection.

handNote.p: This part was copied by Hand A, in Hodegon-style mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in brown ink, with little variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot. There is accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and nomina sacra strokes.

handNote.p: The main text was copied by Hand B, in an upright mixed minuscule script, in brown ink. There is moderate variation in letter size, growing more dramatic towards the end of the manuscript. There are deletions by erasure.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are both angular and round, and angular smooth breathings are sometimes used as apostrophes (e.g. f. 103r, lines 6, 11). Mute iota is subscript, or in a transitional position below and to the right of the letter. There is decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and nomina sacra strokes. The double grave accent is in use.

Distinctive letter-forms include minuscule epsilon with a pronounced curve at the top of the ascender, which is occasionally separate from the lower part of the letter (e.g. f. 93r, lines 9-11); zeta and xi with an undulating tail extending to the right (e.g. f. 3r, lines 10-13, f. 3r, lines 6-9); bulbous open rho (sometimes with inclusions of letters within it, mainly towards the end of the manuscript (e.g. f. 309r)); and an occasional omega with open spiralling loops (e.g. f. 309v, line 10). There are numerous ligatures with open-backed sigma.

Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop. The question mark is occasionally used as a normal punctuation mark (e.g. f. 4r, lines 4-11).
Chapter lists and notes of stichoi have been copied by the same hand in Alexandrine majuscule script.

handDesc.handNote: Marginal rubric has been added by Hand C, in an upright mixed minuscule script, in bright red ink, along with the minor initials and marginal quotation marks. Breathings are both angular and round.
Gospel headings have been added by Hand D, apparently the artist responsible for the ornament,in epigraphic display majuscule script.

decoNote.p: Each Gospel is preceded by a rectangular headpiece, with vegetative ornament, in red ink:-
The text of each Gospel begins with a major initial in the same style as the headpieces, which sometimes forms part of a single connected entity with it.

decoDesc.decoNote: Minor initials in red ink appear at the beginning of lines where an Ammonian section begins, or where it has begun in the course of the previous line.
Line-fillers in red and brown ink accompany the headings for each section of the summary synaxarion (ff. 311r-317v).
Simple vignettes in brown and red ink mark the beginning and end of each chapter list.
The square areas formed by the intersection of vertical and horizontal lines on ff. 3r and 5r have been filled with red paint, which appears to have chemically deteriorated.

additions.p: Notes recording the number of stichoi have been added at the end of each Gospel.

As part of the original production of the manuscript, Hand B has added marginal ÎºÎµÏÎ¬Î»Î±Î¹Î¿Î½ (chapter) numbers and ÏÎ¯ÏÎ»Î¿Î¹ (titles) and Ammonian section numbers in the margins. This hand has also added á¼ÏÏÎ® and ÏÎ­Î»Î¿Ï marks at the beginning and end of lections, although space has not been systematically left for these in the text.
There are occasional marginal corrections and annotations by other hands (e.g. f. 4r).
Running heads for the Gospel and modern chapter number have been added beneath each folio number, in black ink.

history.origin: The characteristics of the script suggest that the manuscript was copied in the 13th century.
